England","Frankley, Worcestershire, England":"Frankley, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Quartermain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Quarterman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Quarterman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Germaine, Marcel, Pascal.","English (Oxfordshire and Surrey): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>quatre mayns</i>, <i>quatre mans</i> ‘four hands’, which has been taken to imply ‘mail-fisted’ but was perhaps used of a skilled craftsman or a dextrous juggler or conjuror."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":3,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Quartermain was born in 1379, in North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, her father, Richard Quartermain II, was 27 and her mother, Joan Grey, was 15. She married Thomas Littleton in 1394, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1421, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England, at the age of 42, and was buried in Worcester, Worcestershire, England."},"et":{"1379–1421":"1379–1421","1357–1422":"1357–1422","1395–1483":"1395–1483","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1379":"1379","1357":"1357","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1483":"1483","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","about 1421":"umbes 1421","1382":"1382","about 1395":"umbes 1395","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Frankley, Worcestershire, England":"Frankley, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"1379–1421":"1379–1421","1357–1422":"1357–1422","1395–1483":"1395–1483","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1379":"1379","1357":"1357","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1483":"1483","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","about 1421":"noin 1421","1382":"1382","about 1395":"noin 1395","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Frankley, Worcestershire, England":"Frankley, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"1379–1421":"1379–1421","1357–1422":"1357–1422